    <table>
      <caption>Grip Fighting</caption>

      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col" style="width: 120px"></th>
          <th scope="col">Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th scope="row">General</th>

          <td>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Grip levels: benign, dangerous (providing lever control or the
                ability to effectively push/pull), deadly (leading to a choke)
              </li>
            </ul>

            <strong>Establishing Grips</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>A grip should enhance your level of control</li>
              <li>
                Strategically, you can start with a benign grip and convert it
                into a better one
              </li>
              <li>
                Directions of control: sagittal, lateral, up/down—ideally, you
                want to control all of these (distance, movement, posture)
              </li>
              <li>
                Grip close to a joint or the end of a lever (e.g., top of the
                spine, wrist, knee)
              </li>
              <li>
                Gripping your opponent’s fingers can be useful (their hands are
                often the closest layer; prevents them from regripping)
              </li>
              <li>
                Be prepared to release the grip and regrip if your opponent
                starts to break your grip
              </li>
              <li>
                Be a diverse grip fighter—a no-gi grip may offer better lever
                control (e.g., ankle vs pant cuff) and be faster to establish
              </li>
              <li>
                To maximize control, roll and rotate (do both when possible) the
                gi material and remove slack—rolling and rotating the material
                forces your opponent to break alignment (due to needing to
                address multiple directions) when attempting to break the grip
              </li>
              <li>To strengthen a grip, block where it has a gap</li>
            </ul>

            <strong>Breaking Grips</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Don’t try to break a grip if your alignment is broken (your grip
                break will be ineffective)
              </li>
              <li>
                To break a grip, break the structure of the gripping limb, then
                take the material in the direction where there is a gap in the
                grip
              </li>
            </ul>

            <strong>Grip Fighting from Seated Guard</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Attack your opponent’s legs, hands, and head to access their
                collar
              </li>
              <li>
                With a collar or sleeve grip: post on your other arm, lift your
                hips, and pull back to break your opponent’s posture forward and
                off-balance them (hang your weight off them like a wrecking
                ball), then transition to a recumbent guard or wrestle-up

                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Do this offensively once you’ve established a collar grip
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Do this defensively if your opponent gets a collar or sleeve
                    grip—grip-match if you can, maintain knee-elbow connection,
                    and then pull them forward
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>
                Beware grips from your opponent that grant them rotational
                control (e.g., cross-side pant cuff, same-side pant cuff +
                same-side collar)—don’t move into a position that will let them
                take advantage of it (you might need to switch your base)
              </li>
              <li>
                If your opponent gets a same-side pant cuff grip, break the grip
                or transition to a recumbent guard and establish leg frames
              </li>
            </ul>

            <strong>Grip Fighting from Recumbent Guard</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>
                If engaging from recumbent guard, you’re relying on
                counterfighting more than on proactive grip fighting
              </li>
              <li>
                Face your opponent from a perpendicular and slanted angle to
                bring your arms closer to the engagement
              </li>
              <li>
                Maintain knee-elbow connection to defend against guard passes
              </li>
              <li>
                Hold your legs in an asymmetric position to make them harder to
                grip simultaneously
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Collar Grip</th>

          <td>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Roll the material into your fingers and then rotate your palm up
              </li>
              <li>
                At the collarbone (more body leverage and material control;
                uncomfortable for your opponent to drive into; threatens a
                choke)
              </li>
            </ul>

            <strong>Same-Side Collar Grip</strong>
            <ul>
              <li></li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>
